%N A173195 Values of n such that 4^x + 4^y + 4^z = n^2 with arbitrary integers x <= y <= z.
%C A173195 We prove that the solutions of 4^x + 4^y + 4^z = n^2 are (x,y,2y-x-1), for any arbitrary integer x,y. We calculate z. 4^x + 4^y + 4^z is square if positive integers m and odd integer t are such as : 1 + 4^(y-x) + 4^(z-x) = (1 + t.2^m)^2, that's why : (1 + 4^(z-y) .( 4^(y-x)) = t(1 + t.2^(m+1)) t.2^(m+1), and then m = 2y - 2x - 1. If we report this value in the precedent equation, we obtain : t-1 = (2^(z-2y+x+1) + t)(2^(z-2y+x+1) - t) . 4^(y-x-1). Because t is odd, z = 2y - x - 1. Finally, this values gives the square (2^x + 2^(2y-x-1))^2 = n^2.
